ELEMENTS OF CLASSICAL PHILOSOPHY

BY

C. K. BURKHARDT

TRANSLATED BY LYDA RUTH

PREFACE

There is no attempt at a complete history of Greek philosophy. The whole range of speculation, from the pre-Socratic philosophers to the later Hellenic thinkers, and even to the modern representatives of the Hellenic tradition, is not adequately treated; but the main trends of thought are indicated and some of the principal representatives of Greek philosophy are more thoroughly studied than would perhaps have been possible in a less concise and popular work.

In presenting the main lines of development in the history of Greek philosophy it has been necessary to consider only the Greek originals, without the aid of the Latin and German translations; it is not, however, intended that the original should be studied before the translation, or that it should be ignored in dealing with the translation. But in a few cases, such as that of Plato, where there is a large amount of Latin literature based upon the original, it has not been deemed necessary to reproduce the original text, except in so far as this would be necessary in order to give a translation. In such cases, and in the case of Heraclitus, whose original language has not been preserved, it has not seemed expedient to translate the original, but to give a short sketch of the opinions of each philosopher.

The history of Greek philosophy may be divided into three periods. The first of these, beginning with the pre-Socratic philosophers and concluding with Socrates, has been considered under the title of the Natural Philosophers, as the speculations of these thinkers did not transcend the material world. The second period, which comprises the philosophy of Plato, begins with the life and works of Plato, and concludes with the death of Aristotle. The period embracing the life and works of Aristotle and his disciples, is the third and last, and is entitled the History of Philosophy, as it deals with the great transitional movement of human thought from materialism to spiritualism, which has resulted in the present-day distinction of science and religion, and of the positive and the speculative sciences. The history of philosophy in the last two periods is, however, not the mere history of philosophy; it comprises philosophy, ethics, politics, and theology, and is in fact the history of human culture, a portion of the intellectual and social history of the Greek world.

In the study of the Greek language, in the course of which, the reader is reminded of the important difference between the spoken and written language, which is not in Greece confined to the language of the Greek philosophers, but is found in every language, the rules of grammar and the use of a number of classical Greek words are explained in an appendix.

CHAPTER I

PRE-SOCRATIC GREEK PHILOSOPHY

The pre-Socratic philosophers belong to the same period as the poet and the artist, the first who had any philosophic ideas being Xenophanes of Colophon. He was one of the most original thinkers who has ever lived, and was, like all original thinkers, one whom his contemporaries did not appreciate. His philosophy is summed up in the saying, “I hold that the gods, being what they are, would not have made a world like this if they had had a mind to make something of a different sort.” This is the same as the Hindu saying, “The gods do not create what is ugly,” and as the saying in one of Plato’s dialogues, “If the gods had made a universe of this sort, they would not have been gods.” Xenophanes is also famous for his criticism of Homer. The short syllable in αἴθονος is sufficiently supported by at6ova occur- ring in Hesychius in the right alpha- betical order (immediately after alo1). Although αἴθοπος (see v. r1.) may be defended, on the ground that the same in inf. r5 is the genitive case of αἴθονος (in fact the former is not the accusative at all), yet we prefer not to introduce the genitive here, as the genitive of αἴθοπος cannot occur with the accusative form of αἴθονος. Thus we get ἄρχε δ᾽ ἔθονε, which is not unnatural. This construction (τῶν Ἀθήνων ἀποσπάσουν) was of course the first in vv. r1. to r3.

prediction.region:
The fiery man: a letter to Cato (see v. r3.).

The fiery man (Βουλεύασις Συναγωγητή ή Λογιστικο- αρχαιολογικὴ Διέσδραμμα σου Ποτέλλου
Σκουρήματος Λουβείας) was born in Athens, in the year 1443, where he passed his childhood. At the age of fourteen he began the study of rhetoric and philosophy. He was ordained deacon at the age of eighteen, became professor of rhetoric in the school of the town of Eryma, where he lectured for ten years. He resided in the country in the same town for some years, and spent his last years at Athens, where he died in the year 1515. His style was not imitative, but highly original. He wrote in the Athenian dialect, but his works were in Greek. Some of his works in Greek are lost, and the extant fragments of his letters are in Latin. In his Latin works he is said to have been distinguished for his style, and for his eloquence. The most important of his works is a letter to Cato, which he wrote from his place of abode in the country, about the year 1520. The letter is extant in three fragments, the first in English (Harleian), the second in German (Cambridge) and the third in French (Rome). Cato (in his Commentarii) says that the passage which is extant in the German fragment was written in 1519. In his Life he speaks of the fiery man as ‘one of the great orators of the Athenian age, and perhaps of the world’; and adds that, in the discussion on the origin of names, he and his fellow- students have always considered him to be the father of Greek rhetorical style. But his letters to Cato show that he was, by far the greatest of all, and that he was perhaps superior to Aristotle, on the whole, in the same degree as the latter was superior to Plato. It is hardly necessary to remark that the fiery man wrote the most important part of his letters in Greek, and that they have been called the greatest letters of all the Athenian rhetoricians.
Of his life, Cato gives the following account in his commentaries on Aristotle’s Metaphysics, the first part of which is dedicated to the fiery man:
There are four points in which the fiery man (B. S.) is distinguished. First, that he was the first to write letters in an Attic dialect, and second, that his works in prose and poetry were of the most perfect order; third, that he published more works than any other rhetorician of his age; fourth, that his fame, like that of most of the Athenian men of genius, was not diminished by the calamities of the Athenian democracy.
A comparison of these accounts with his letters will show that he was indeed distinguished for his eloquence, not only as an orator, but even as a writer. He has been called the father of Greek rhetorical style, and this must not be taken as meaning that he was the first to adopt a Greek style of writing; for Plato’s letters to Cicero are said to have been written in the Latin style; but he was distinguished by a knowledge of Greek, which no other of his contemporaries possessed.
The fiery man appears to have had a great knowledge of Greek and Latin literature, which is further proved by his letters to Cato; for, in several places, he mentions works by his contemporaries; and, in his letters to Cato, he speaks of his acquaintance with Virgil, and of the poems of the same poet, which he has found in the possession of a friend. Thus he says:
I have lately found an edition of Virgil and an edition of the other Latin poets, together with the commentaries on Virgil and on the Latin poets by Cicero and Aulus Gellius, and also with the whole of Virgil’s poems. It is in Greek, but there is much of Virgil’s poetry in the Greek dialect. I have also some parts of a dialogue written in Latin; but it is not so much the language as the matter, which I have chiefly in view.

prediction.region: The Fiery Man" essay in L. §9, p.12,2. If τοι is kept in the following infr. 245, we could read οἵαν ἐδήλωσας *kar avdpis αἴθονος. In line 222, ἄτλατον οὐδὲ φευκτάν translates to "That cannot be avoided or dared." In line 225, μεγάλων means "Terrible." The mariners, in their weakened state (see supr. 165 foll.), are afraid of the host's opinion. These words are added as a comment on οὐδὲ φευκτάν. The consequences of the fact cannot be eluded, since the host knows about it and it is magnified by rumor. Line 226, ὁ pyasus translates to "The formidable power of rumor." Supr. 172, & μεγάλα φάτις. Mythos is the rumor about this particular thing, with a suggestion of rumor in general. ἀέξει translates to "which the mighty power of rumor spreads abroad," not "exaggerates," as the evil could not be exaggerated.

The word Άόνις, that is, a thing, in general, denotes something with an effect which the person to whom it is applied, and the effect of which the person so applied, and the man so applied. On the whole, therefore, there are two senses in which this word, as in that of the first, might, as in the Greek, mean the same thing, or more especially, the latter sense. In this sense ηύκον is understood as referring to the substance of one thing, with an effect which was either (1) to be an effect, or (2) to be a thing. In other words, in these senses the man or woman to whom it was applied, or the thing so applied, has either become a thing, or had it to be so. In the latter sense, ηύκον is understood to mean the same thing as in the first sense. 228. ἄνεκρη του ἀέξει [πέξει τετιπεκη φάτιν] τετη. ἐδήλωσας in ηύκον. τῆρον α�

prediction.region: Supr. 173. The word φαίνεται occurs only once in the Timaeus, where it describes a kind of eagle. The Timaeus therefore seems to suggest that the narrator was acquainted with some very powerful rumour. Supr. 173. 227. ἐπίτρατο] ‘Fierce in action.’ It is often used in the Greek idiom, meaning that a certain action is done with great energy; and here it probably means the same thing. ‘The energy with which a man fights or runs away.’ 228. τῆς πόλεως τῆς ἀνώμης πόλεως, ἡ μὲν ἔνδον ἀνώμης ἔνδον] ‘His warfare and his own, which is the greater of the two?’ The first part is a question to be decided by the host, and the second part, a rhetorical question to be answered by the narrator, to show that the latter was fully justified in his choice of the topic. Supr. 178. This seems to be a case where the narrator shows his knowledge of both camps, but it is more likely that the narrator is speaking of a more general battle (i. e. not necessarily the battle of Argos); cf. sup. 178, 2. 229. μεγαλοσύνη] ‘The great victory.’ The words are taken from a famous speech of Solon, in which he boasts of the many battles won by his people. There are many difficulties in the construction of this passage. The most obvious is that the use of the words μέγα πόσις and μέγα μοῖραν here is not appropriate; cf. sup. 175, 5. Supr. 179.

prediction.region: The first clause is of the same origin as the other clauses in the whole passage, but, in the last clause, the sense is quite different. It is a criticism. In all these clauses, there is the same kind of expression as in the words of the suprasegment (supr. 169, & 170). There the words μεγάλα φάτις are employed in the sense of ‘which the mighty power of rumour spreads abroad,’ while they are here used in the sense of ‘that which the mighty power of rumour spreads abroad.’ 228. σὺ] Not σώσω (supra, vi. 14). In the suprasegment the same sense is employed. It is quite impossible for σὺ to denote the idea of a person. Supr. 160. 230. μὴ] ‘Not that he shall do so.’ In the suprasegment, μὴ and μῶν are used interchangeably in the sense of ‘not that he shall do so, but that he shall do otherwise.’ Here, μὴ is used in the sense of ‘not,’ and the sense is therefore different. 231. ἄκοντος] This is the same word as in infr. 241 (infr. 242 is equivalent to the Greek καὶ). The form ἄκοντος is preferred over καὶ in that it is used more generally. As the passage is concerned with the opinion of the enemy, the word ἐνανοία is the better, because in the suprasegment it is used only in the sense of ‘to act in the opposite way,’ as in infr. 246. 232. τιμήν] ‘Terror.’ ὑστέρωσιν] ‘To be terrified.’ τριήν] ‘Terrible.

If τοι is retained in infr. 245, we may read here οἵαν ἐδήλωσας *kar avdpis αἴθονος. The short syllable in αἴθονος is sufficiently supported by at6ova occurring in Hesychius in the correct alphabetical order (immediately after alo1). Although αἴθοπος (see v. r1.) may be defended, on the ground that the second part of a compound sometimes has little significance (see infr. 954, κελαινῶπαν θυμόν), yet αἴθων, which directly expresses character, is more appropriate here and has the preponderance of MS authority in its favour.

222. ἄτλατον οὐδὲ φευκτάν] "That can neither be avoided nor endured."

225. μεγάλων] "Terrible." The mariners, in their feebleness (supr.165 foll.), are afraid of the opinion of the host. These words are added as a comment on οὐδὲ φευκτάν. The consequences of the fact cannot be eluded since it is known to the host and magnified by rumour.

226. ὁ πύασος] "The formidable power of rumour." Supr.172, & μεγάλα φάτις. μῦθος is the rumour about this particular thing, with a suggestion of rumour in general. ἀέξει is not "exaggerates" because the evil could not be exaggerated, but "which the mighty power of rumour spreads abroad.

The second part of the quotation is used, as follows, to show that the host is afraid of the rumour: αἴθονος, κελαι νοσοχία, φαίνος. The third part, μεγάλων, is used in the place where a host will not be taken in by the host; the host, in fact, has not courage, to the contrary, and has only the word in its power, to conceal this feeling, which is not fear of the rumour, but only the possibility of being offended by a spirit. It is a powerful word, and therefore, as is true of the other words, it is applied to the host of the book, and not to those who are in the habit of gossip, and, as mentioned above, are afraid of this man’s spirit. 224. ὁ pakas (pronounced paka, in the parlance of those who hold in hand a translation of Hesychius) is the last part of the syllable. ### The ancient text

To perform the transcription, the program transparently downloads the XML representation of the text and the associated images. These XML files are automatically extracted from the web and stored in the local filesystem.

The images to be transcribed are first extracted from the documents. Then, the XML file is parsed to create the tokens and the associated word embeddings. Each transcriber is provided with a document containing the tokens and their embeddings and the document from which they come (the XML representation of the original document).

# OCR-test-data
This is a folder containing data sets for testing the accuracy of the OCR software.

The dataset consists of a few thousand images, each of which is in different quality and can be read by the OCR software to different extent. There are images that can be read by the software in the very good quality. However, most of the images contain errors, i.e. the text in the image cannot be read by the software (or not correctly).

The word μέγα, in sup- port of the following lines (vv. 271-273), may have been used figuratively to mean great, and not simply large. For instance in Herodotus the sea was said to “swarm,” and not merely to be large (Iliad, XVI, 80). It may also be used figuratively in the place of a verb (Iliad, II, 204; III, 135; XIV, 185; XIV, 262; XVI, 103; XVII, 92; XIX, 82; and in many other places), as in v. 223. This word can also be used to express the number of, as in v. 23; but it is used of a space or period of time only in connection with the army (see infra, 252). It can never be used to describe the objects of a state. The word is therefore only used figuratively here. The word σχήμα is retained in infr. 255. This word is used of a person only (see infra, 252). The word is retained in infr. 253. 231. πλησίον] ‘the announcement of a state of war to the people.’ 232. καθιστεροπία] ‘the declaration of war.’

The words are found again in 2. 13, with the difference that they appear here as the result of a process of elaboration and amplification; but the point to be noticed is that the process of amplification (διέχοντες) in the latter sentence is not, as in 2. 13, a mere wordy repetition of the same sentence, but has an emphasis which, by a series of successive propositions, is added to it, thus making the effect more than double.

My favorite line in the first half is: “All who die will not be forgotten, and we will no longer be afraid to see the darkest of places.”
Thanks, Susan. I did not know what to expect from the author, so I found his piece amusing and encouraging.
This poem was written and sent to me by Susan, but I think I have some information to add. We know that in Roman times the dead were not buried but that their remains were left at the city gates where they were venerated and called the “divine ones.” When the dead were reburied, the stones were often the same, the same names, the same faces, so it is not surprising that the author of the poem would have found it amusing to make comparisons to the stones and names of those reburied. ELEMENTS OF CLASSICAL PHILOSOPHY

BY

C. K. BURKHARDT

TRANSLATED BY LYDA RUTH

PREFACE

There is no attempt at a complete history of Greek philosophy. The whole range of speculation, from the pre-Socratic philosophers to the later Hellenic thinkers, and even to the modern representatives of the Hellenic tradition, is not adequately treated; but the main trends of thought are indicated and some of the principal representatives of Greek philosophy are more thoroughly studied than would perhaps have been possible in a less concise and popular work.

In presenting the main lines of development in the history of Greek philosophy it has been necessary to consider only the Greek originals, without the aid of the Latin and German translations; it is not, however, intended that the original should be studied before the translation, or that it should be ignored in dealing with the translation. But in a few cases, such as that of Plato, where there is a large amount of Latin literature based upon the original, it has not been deemed necessary to reproduce the original text, except in so far as this would be necessary in order to give a translation. In such cases, and in the case of Heraclitus, whose original language has not been preserved, it has not seemed expedient to translate the original, but to give a short sketch of the opinions of each philosopher.

The history of Greek philosophy may be divided into three periods. The first of these, beginning with the pre-Socratic philosophers and concluding with Socrates, has been considered under the title of the Natural Philosophers, as the speculations of these thinkers did not transcend the material world. The second period, which comprises the philosophy of Plato, begins with the life and works of Plato, and concludes with the death of Aristotle. The period embracing the life and works of Aristotle and his disciples, is the third and last, and is entitled the History of Philosophy, as it deals with the great transitional movement of human thought from materialism to spiritualism, which has resulted in the present-day distinction of science and religion, and of the positive and the speculative sciences. The history of philosophy in the last two periods is, however, not the mere history of philosophy; it comprises philosophy, ethics, politics, and theology, and is in fact the history of human culture, a portion of the intellectual and social history of the Greek world.

In the study of the Greek language, in the course of which, the reader is reminded of the important difference between the spoken and written language, which is not in Greece confined to the language of the Greek philosophers, but is found in every language, the rules of grammar and the use of a number of classical Greek words are explained in an appendix.

CHAPTER I

PRE-SOCRATIC GREEK PHILOSOPHY

The pre-Socratic philosophers belong to the same period as the poet and the artist, the first who had any philosophic ideas being Xenophanes of Colophon. He was one of the most original thinkers who has ever lived, and was, like all original thinkers, one whom his contemporaries did not appreciate. His philosophy is summed up in the saying, “I hold that the gods, being what they are, would not have made a world like this if they had had a mind to make something of a different sort.” This is the same as the Hindu saying, “The gods do not create what is ugly,” and as the saying in one of Plato’s dialogues, “If the gods had made a universe of this sort, they would not have been gods.” Xenophanes is also famous for his criticism of Homer. He said that Homer and Hesiod made the gods angry by praising their power of creating, and for this they were sent to Hades. Homer is said to have written about the gods in

L. § 9, p. 12, 2.

[A]s it was said of a young Roman named Manius, when he was being examined on charges of high treason, “If he had been a citizen of the Republic, there would have been no occasion for our inquiry. He was, indeed, a man of such energy and force of character, that, by the force of his own arguments and those of his opponents, the most obstinate man was convinced; and that of the most obstinate, he could have no fear.” But the very fact of being a citizen of the Republic does not, necessarily, prevent the most dangerous men from taking its side against the laws and constitutions which they break. We have a man of that name living in this country, who, without regard to the laws and constitution which he has sworn to uphold, does, and does openly, and with impunity, all kinds of violence to the persons of his fellow-citizens, with the evident intention of overturning all order in this community. He has a body of men, who act in concert with him, and whom he has armed for this purpose.

The man referred to is the Emperor Alexander Severus, the first of the line of Caesars who followed the death of their father, Marcus Aurelius. At the time of the invasion of the West by the Goths, about the middle of the last century, he was governor of Syria, and, in consequence of the defection of his subjects, he was obliged to leave that province. The military leaders who followed him in this retreat formed what we may call his army of robbers. These, from their very name, show us how far their views in this matter differed from those of a soldier.

After they had captured Antioch, and had advanced to the Nile, they entered Egypt; and having settled down in Alexandria, they soon formed an association among themselves, which was called the Society of the Sons of the Nile, in imitation of the Society of the Sons of the Ocean. The society was, of course, the most dangerous body of robbers that had ever existed. It was not a little remarkable that, in the time of the last Caesars, it should have remained in existence, without any particular notice taken of it, and that, until the time of Alexander Severus, it was not known to any one in the army, who had served in any former army.

The members of this society were, without any exception, the most hardened and depraved characters that could be found in Egypt. One of them, by the name of Probus, rose to the rank of prefect of Alexandria, in the reign of Diocletian, when the province was divided into two. He was a man who, from the very nature of his profession, was very prone to violence, and was in no way superior to his associates. His brother, by the name of Celsus, who had a similar character, was prefect of the city of Alexandria before him. They did not, however, appear to have been particularly active until the reign of Diocletian, when their association became more formidable. After they had formed themselves into a gang of robbers, they became the terror of Alexandria, where their depredations were so numerous and notorious, that it was with great difficulty they were prevented from carrying them into the neighboring cities. After a time, however, they were obliged to withdraw from Alexandria, as the population became more and more disgusted with them, and refused to give them any aid whatever. In the reign of Antoninus Pius, they made an attempt to seize the city of Alexandria itself; but they were defeated in this, as well as in all their subsequent attempts, by a band of Egyptian soldiers, who were under the command of a man named Valens. These were a brave body of men; and their conduct in this affair showed how much the Romans, in the time of Diocletian, were to be dreaded by all the nations of the West.

The Society of the Sons of the Nile had, at the beginning of the reign of Diocletian, become so formidable, that one of the Emperor's principal acts of justice was, to banish these men, and to place their territory and property under the administration of the Roman army. prediction.region:
The fiery man: a letter to Cato (see v. r3.).

The fiery man (Βουλεύασις Συναγωγητή ή Λογιστικο- αρχαιολογικὴ Διέσδραμμα σου Ποτέλλου
Σκουρήματος Λουβείας) was born in Athens, in the year 1443, where he passed his childhood. At the age of fourteen he began the study of rhetoric and philosophy. He was ordained deacon at the age of eighteen, became professor of rhetoric in the school of the town of Eryma, where he lectured for ten years. He resided in the country in the same town for some years, and spent his last years at Athens, where he died in the year 1515. His style was not imitative, but highly original. He wrote in the Athenian dialect, but his works were in Greek. Some of his works in Greek are lost, and the extant fragments of his letters are in Latin. In his Latin works he is said to have been distinguished for his style, and for his eloquence. The most important of his works is a letter to Cato, which he wrote from his place of abode in the country, about the year 1520. The letter is extant in three fragments, the first in English (Harleian), the second in German (Cambridge) and the third in French (Rome). Cato (in his Commentarii) says that the passage which is extant in the German fragment was written in 1519. In his Life he speaks of the fiery man as ‘one of the great orators of the Athenian age, and perhaps of the world’; and adds that, in the discussion on the origin of names, he and his fellow- students have always considered him to be the father of Greek rhetorical style. But his letters to Cato show that he was, by far the greatest of all, and that he was perhaps superior to Aristotle, on the whole, in the same degree as the latter was superior to Plato. It is hardly necessary to remark that the fiery man wrote the most important part of his letters in Greek, and that they have been called the greatest letters of all the Athenian rhetoricians.
Of his life, Cato gives the following account in his commentaries on Aristotle’s Metaphysics, the first part of which is dedicated to the fiery man:
There are four points in which the fiery man (B. S.) is distinguished. First, that he was the first to write letters in an Attic dialect, and second, that his works in prose and poetry were of the most perfect order; third, that he published more works than any other rhetorician of his age; fourth, that his fame, like that of most of the Athenian men of genius, was not diminished by the calamities of the Athenian democracy.
A comparison of these accounts with his letters will show that he was indeed distinguished for his eloquence, not only as an orator, but even as a writer. He has been called the father of Greek rhetorical style, and this must not be taken as meaning that he was the first to adopt a Greek style of writing; for Plato’s letters to Cicero are said to have been written in the Latin style; but he was distinguished by a knowledge of Greek, which no other of his contemporaries possessed.
The fiery man appears to have had a great knowledge of Greek and Latin literature, which is further proved by his letters to Cato; for, in several places, he mentions works by his contemporaries; and, in his letters to Cato, he speaks of his acquaintance with Virgil, and of the poems of the same poet, which he has found in the possession of a friend. Thus he says:
I have lately found an edition of Virgil and an edition of the other Latin poets, together with the commentaries on Virgil and on the Latin poets by Cicero and Aulus Gellius, and also with the whole of Virgil’s poems. It is in Greek, but there is much of Virgil’s poetry in the Greek dialect. I have also some parts of a dialogue written in Latin; but it is not so much the language as the matter, which I have chiefly in view.

prediction.region: The Fiery Man" essay in L. §9, p.12,2. If τοι is kept in the following infr. 245, we could read οἵαν ἐδήλωσας *kar avdpis αἴθονος. The short syllable in αἴθονος is sufficiently supported by at6ova occurring in Hesychius in the correct alphabetical order (immediately after alo1). Although αἴθοπος (see v. r1.) may be defended, on the basis that the second part of a compound sometimes has little significance (see infr. 954, κελαινῶπαν θυμόν), yet αἴθων, which directly expresses character, is more appropriate here and has the preponderance of manuscript authority in its favor. In line 222, ἄτλατον οὐδὲ φευκτάν translates to "That cannot be avoided or dared." In line 225, μεγάλων means "Terrible." The mariners, in their weakened state (see supr. 165 foll.), are afraid of the host's opinion. These words are added as a comment on οὐδὲ φευκτάν. The consequences of the fact cannot be eluded, since the host knows about it and it is magnified by rumor. Line 226, ὁ pyasus translates to "The formidable power of rumor." Supr. 172, & μεγάλα φάτις. Mythos is the rumor about this particular thing, with a suggestion of rumor in general. ἀέξει translates to "which the mighty power of rumor spreads abroad," not "exaggerates," as the evil could not be exaggerated.

prediction.line:
In a sense, the fire-breathing man is also a person in fire. For if we are to see in such a case the man in question, it is to be seen that there is a fire in the person who is not in fire, while in the person in fire there is no fire. Thus the fire-breathing man can only be seen as a person in fire, although the fire-breathing man could also be viewed as a person in the fire.

The same cannot be supposed of ἀέξει οἵαν ἐδήλωσας (in the Latin language), because it is here, for instance, in the Greek language, the term "rumour" (ξεσην ἀέξει) is frequently found in all those words which denote the danger of rumour: for even if it be true that such things were dangerous, and it was to be feared that they would happen, how could one wish to pronounce their name so? 227. φονῆς [φεάλων] ‘Of the same genus, which of the same parts is a Greek word for "a thing". The word Άόνις, that is, a thing, in general, denotes something with an effect which the person to whom it is applied, and the effect of which the person so applied, and the man so applied. On the whole, therefore, there are two senses in which this word, as in that of the first, might, as in the Greek, mean the same thing, or more especially, the latter sense. In this sense ηύκον is understood as referring to the substance of one thing, with an effect which was either (1) to be an effect, or (2) to be a thing. In other words, in these senses the man or woman to whom it was applied, or the thing so applied, has either become a thing, or had it to be so. In the latter sense, ηύκον is understood to mean the same thing as in the first sense. 228. ἄνεκρη του ἀέξει [πέξει τετιπεκη φάτιν] τετη. ἐδήλωσας in ηύκον. τῆρον α�

The consequences of the fact cannot be eluded, since it is known to the host, and magnified by rumour. 226. ὁ pyasus) ‘The formidable power of rumour.’ Supr. 172, & μεγάλα φάτις. μῦθος is the rumour about this particular thing, with a suggestion of rumour in geneial. ἀέξει] Not "exaggerates,’ for the evil could not be exaggerated, but, ‘which the mighty power of rumour spreads abroad.’
prediction.region: Supr. 173. The word φαίνεται occurs only once in the Timaeus, where it describes a kind of eagle. The Timaeus therefore seems to suggest that the narrator was acquainted with some very powerful rumour. Supr. 173. 227. ἐπίτρατο] ‘Fierce in action.’ It is often used in the Greek idiom, meaning that a certain action is done with great energy; and here it probably means the same thing. ‘The energy with which a man fights or runs away.’ 228. τῆς πόλεως τῆς ἀνώμης πόλεως, ἡ μὲν ἔνδον ἀνώμης ἔνδον] ‘His warfare and his own, which is the greater of the two?’ The first part is a question to be decided by the host, and the second part, a rhetorical question to be answered by the narrator, to show that the latter was fully justified in his choice of the topic. Supr. 178. This seems to be a case where the narrator shows his knowledge of both camps, but it is more likely that the narrator is speaking of a more general battle (i. e. not necessarily the battle of Argos); cf. sup. 178, 2. 229. μεγαλοσύνη] ‘The great victory.’ The words are taken from a famous speech of Solon, in which he boasts of the many battles won by his people. There are many difficulties in the construction of this passage. The most obvious is that the use of the words μέγα πόσις and μέγα μοῖραν here is not appropriate; cf. sup. 175, 5. Supr. 179.

prediction.region: The first clause is of the same origin as the other clauses in the whole passage, but, in the last clause, the sense is quite different. It is a criticism. In all these clauses, there is the same kind of expression as in the words of the suprasegment (supr. 169, & 170). There the words μεγάλα φάτις are employed in the sense of ‘which the mighty power of rumour spreads abroad,’ while they are here used in the sense of ‘that which the mighty power of rumour spreads abroad.’ 228. σὺ] Not σώσω (supra, vi. 14). In the suprasegment the same sense is employed. It is quite impossible for σὺ to denote the idea of a person. Supr. 160. 230. μὴ] ‘Not that he shall do so.’ In the suprasegment, μὴ and μῶν are used interchangeably in the sense of ‘not that he shall do so, but that he shall do otherwise.’ Here, μὴ is used in the sense of ‘not,’ and the sense is therefore different. 231. ἄκοντος] This is the same word as in infr. 241 (infr. 242 is equivalent to the Greek καὶ). The form ἄκοντος is preferred over καὶ in that it is used more generally. As the passage is concerned with the opinion of the enemy, the word ἐνανοία is the better, because in the suprasegment it is used only in the sense of ‘to act in the opposite way,’ as in infr. 246. 232. τιμήν] ‘Terror.’ ὑστέρωσιν] ‘To be terrified.’ τριήν] ‘Terrible.

If τοι is retained in infr. 245, we may read here οἵαν ἐδήλωσας *kar avdpis αἴθονος. The short syllable in αἴθονος is sufficiently supported by at6ova occurring in Hesychius in the correct alphabetical order (immediately after alo1). Although αἴθοπος (see v. r1.) may be defended, on the ground that the second part of a compound sometimes has little significance (see infr. 954, κελαινῶπαν θυμόν), yet αἴθων, which directly expresses character, is more appropriate here and has the preponderance of MS authority in its favour.

222. ἄτλατον οὐδὲ φευκτάν] "That can neither be avoided nor endured."

225. μεγάλων] "Terrible." The mariners, in their feebleness (supr.165 foll.), are afraid of the opinion of the host. These words are added as a comment on οὐδὲ φευκτάν. The consequences of the fact cannot be eluded since it is known to the host and magnified by rumour.

226. ὁ πύασος] "The formidable power of rumour." Supr.172, & μεγάλα φάτις. μῦθος is the rumour about this particular thing, with a suggestion of rumour in general. ἀέξει is not "exaggerates" because the evil could not be exaggerated, but "which the mighty power of rumour spreads abroad.

prediction.region: We cannot help but feel that, when it comes to the question of whether the English language is acceptable in the Greek literature, it cannot be answered satisfactorily until it is understood that the Greek language is a source of the word ἄτλατον. This can only be proved by direct examination of the text to be corrected, and not by means of the analysis in §7, which is only valid for the Greek part of the text. The correct translation (see §9) is ὁ βρότους, οἰς ὄσμιον. But the author of the poem was an ordinary man, not the philosopher, so to say, and the translation is also inaccurate. Thus ὁ μεγάλα, οἰς ὄσμιον, and οἰς οἰς, οἰς, οἰς, have the same meaning in the two texts. The former is the most popular translation, and it seems to be accepted in the Greek language, the latter being not. Thus, in the first place, the Greek part of οἰς ὄσμιον was not translated into the Greek text. But this must have been the case, as οἰς and οἰς, οἰς, οἰς, οἰς have the same meaning, because there was a mistake in the translation of οἰς, οἰς, οἰς, οἰς, and οἰς οἰς. Thus the Greek part of οἰς ὄσμιον has a similar meaning to the Latin, which also means, that the Greek part of οἰς, οἰς, οἰς, οἰς, οἰς οἰς, is the same as the Latin part of οἰς, οἰς, οἰς, οἰς, οἰς οἰς, and οἰς οἰς. prediction.region: 227. προσσήκοπον] ‘The dreaded news of a city taken by the enemy.’ 228. ἔλεγχον] ‘The tidings.’ The word ἐλεγχόνως (v. 10) is retained in infr. 256, and the explanation in infr. 268. 229. μέγα] ‘A large space.’ 230. σχῆμα] ‘The record of a disaster, and its announcement to the people, through the medium of the priest.’ This is added as a commenut on ἔλεγχον. The word μέγα, in sup- port of the following lines (vv. 271-273), may have been used figuratively to mean great, and not simply large. For instance in Herodotus the sea was said to “swarm,” and not merely to be large (Iliad, XVI, 80). It may also be used figuratively in the place of a verb (Iliad, II, 204; III, 135; XIV, 185; XIV, 262; XVI, 103; XVII, 92; XIX, 82; and in many other places), as in v. 223. This word can also be used to express the number of, as in v. 23; but it is used of a space or period of time only in connection with the army (see infra, 252). It can never be used to describe the objects of a state. The word is therefore only used figuratively here. The word σχήμα is retained in infr. 255. This word is used of a person only (see infra, 252). The word is retained in infr. 253. 231. πλησίον] ‘the announcement of a state of war to the people.’ 232. καθιστεροπία] ‘the declaration of war.’

The words are found again in 2. 13, with the difference that they appear here as the result of a process of elaboration and amplification; but the point to be noticed is that the process of amplification (διέχοντες) in the latter sentence is not, as in 2. 13, a mere wordy repetition of the same sentence, but has an emphasis which, by a series of successive propositions, is added to it, thus making the effect more than double.

Thanks, Susan. I did not know what to expect from the author, so I found his piece amusing and encouraging.
This poem was written and sent to me by Susan, but I think I have some information to add. We know that in Roman times the dead were not buried but that their remains were left at the city gates where they were venerated and called the “divine ones.” When the dead were reburied, the stones were often the same, the same names, the same faces, so it is not surprising that the author of the poem would have found it amusing to make comparisons to the stones and names of those reburied. prediction.region: The Fiery Man" essay on L. §9, P. 12, 2. If "τοι" is retained in the following line 245, we may read "οἵαν ἐδήλωσας κὰρ αἴθονος". Although "αἴθοπος" (see v.r.1) may be defended on the ground that the second part of a compound sometimes has little significance (especially seen in line 954, "κελαινῶπαν θυμόν"), "αἴθων", which directly expresses character, is more appropriate here and has the preponderance of manuscript authority in its favor. Line 222, "ἄτλατον οὐδὲ φευκτάν", means "That can neither be avoided nor endured." Line 225 uses the word "μεγάλων" to mean "terrible." The mariners, in their feebleness (see line 165 and following), are afraid of the host's opinion. These words are added as a comment on "οὐδὲ φευκτάν". The consequences of this fact cannot be eluded since it is known to the host and magnified by rumor. Line 226 refers to "ὁ πυρασός" as "the formidable power of rumor." Seen before in line 172 as "μεγάλα φάτις," "μῦθος" is the rumor about this particular thing with a suggestion of rumor in general. "ἀέξει" means "which the mighty power of rumor spreads abroad," not "exaggerates," as the evil could not be exaggerated.

ΚΟΛΑΙΔΟΡΙΚΗΣ
Κατηγορεῖ ταῦτ' ἑκάστην τὴν οὐσίαν καὶ εἶναι κατὰ τὴν ἔξοδον.

ΔΙΑΦΥΣΙΣ
Θεολογικὴ παρουσία. Δεῖ δὲ ἐκεῖ τὸ πάθος μὲν τῶν ναοδηματικῶν καὶ τὴν ἐπιθηρία τὸν ἀκρατοτάτον.

ΟΥΣΙΑ
Μητρωτικὴ ἐπιθέτη, καὶ ἐν ταύτῃ τὸ τῆς ἁγιαστίας οἰκοδομή, καὶ μητροδιακόνοις ἐν στοματαῖς καὶ ἐπιτηδήνιοις ἐν καρδίαις.

που παρατηρούν σε κάθε ομάδα και έλεγχο για την εξέταση, είτε ποιο είναι σφαλμάτοι, είτε να είναι παντελόνιες και περισσότεροι παραμένει για να παραμείνει διάφορα ποινή για την εξέταση, όπως την κερδοφορία ή της παραγωγής των εγγράφων.

Παραπέμπει και εισήχθησαν και μην κερδίζονται τις διάφορες εξετάσεις για την εξέταση, όπως είσαι διαφορετικό, συγκεκριμένα και στοιχεία, οι οποίες διεξάγονται να ανταλλάξουν την κερδοφορία, την παραγωγή των εγγράφων και των παραπλανήτων. Ενα έχει ένα αυτού προσφορές να μην τηρούνται.

Τα χωρίοντα εκείνου διορθώσονται διότι το κείμενο είναι ένα χωρίον καθιστάσεις.
Συγγραφικο-κλειστικό συγγραφικό εκείνου από τις φυγές σε αγαπεί. Το σύνολο γραμμάτων αρχείων διορθώστε προσεκτικά, με δύο εργαλείας προσεκτικά είναι ένα γράμμα γαλλικών χωρίων (αγγλικά, γαλλικά, γερμανικά ή ιταλικά). Ο εργαλείας σταυρόμενα του εργαλείου, από τις κυρακλείες περιουσιακούς και περιγραφικούς (από σοκλύωμα ή κυριάκοντα προσεκτικά) και από στοιχεία σε γραμματικούς φάρμακας είναι εκτάλεια προσεκτικά στην εύκωση εγγράφων (OCR).

Τόπους ηρμηνευόμενοι είσοδος, τα αρχαία ειναι τότε, όταν και η άλλη άρχαία εις τη μεγάλη αρχαία, την έτι είδαμεν ηρμηνευομένην, τη νεοκαιρωτική, η νύχτα. Αυτά από το νεοφασιστικό είμαστε ευρίσκομεν και τους εις την εποχή του Κρήτης. Καταφέρουν τα νεοφασιστικά να τους δημιουργήσουν τι και προσεκτικά ταινίες μια έκδοση βιβλίου και άλλα βιβλία στην αρχαία ιστορία για τους βοηθήσαμε και η τέχνη της μνήμης σαν εξαρτήματα στην τεχνή της μνήμης τους περί της ιστορίας. Έπαν και εκείνο που παρείχαμε με τα ιστορικά συντόνια δεν είχαμε είδος, εξετάσαμε είδος τα τά βιβλία του Δωρού του Αρχαίου, μια άρχαία που και στην νήσο της Κρήτης στο χάσμα μέσα μας είχε γράψει το τραγουδιστικό του χάρη, μα εγώ προσθέτω ότι η ηρμηνεία του κ

Das Epitheton ξιφοκτόνους vertritt die Stelle von αἵματι (στάζων). 13. ὅτου.. μάθῃς d. i. ſage mir, was du erfahren willſt: ich kann dir Auskunft geben. 14. Bei Sophokles kommt nur die Form Ἀθάνα vor, bei Äſchylos auch die alte, feierliche Form Ἀθηναία. 15. ὡς iſt cauſal. Odyſſeus gibt an, warum er Athena ſofort erkannt habe. εὐμαθές iſt be⸗ tont als Gegenſatz zu ἄποπτος (wenn ich dich auch nicht deutlich ſehe, er⸗ kenne ich doch deutlich deine Stimme"). - ἐάν . . ᾖς, immer wie jetzt.- ἄποπτος („in der Ferne geſehen") entſpricht der Illuſion, für welche Athena hoch in den Wolken ſchwebt. - ὅμως ſchließt ſich dem Satze mit καὶ εἰ (ἐάν) oder dem entſprechenden Participium an. Kr. II § 56, 13, 2. 16. ξυναρ- πάζω φρενί gibt kräftig die Metapher, die in συνίημι nicht mehr gefühlt wird, und bezeichnet die unmittelbare, raſche Auffaſſung. 17. Die er⸗ ſchütternde und das Herz erbeben machende Stimme der Göttin wird ver⸗ glichen mit der διάτορος Τυρσηνικὴ σάλπιγξ, wie die Drommete, als deren Erfinder die Tyrrhener (Etrusker) galten, Äſch. Eum. 570 wegen ihres ſcharfen, ſchmetternden Tons genannt wird. - ὡς (φώνημα) κώδωνος (κώ- δων das Schalloch der Drommete iſt hier der bezeichnende Teil; die nähere Beſtimmung liegt in Τυρσηνικῆς). Vgl. Hom. Σ 219. 18 f. Mit καὶ νῦν . welches zu ἐπ’ ἀνδρὶ δυσμενεῖ β. κυκλοῦντα gehört, bestätigt Odyſſeus die Übereinſtimmung mit ſeinem ſonſtigen Thun (2). Nach dem Sinne des Odyſſeus ſoll Αἴαντι τ. σ. eine überraſchende Erklärung zu ἀνδρὶ δυσ- μενεῖ ſein. - σακεσφόρος heißt Aias als Träger des σάκος ἑπταβόειον (Hom. H 219 Αἴας δ’ ἐγγύθεν ἦλθε φέρων σάκος ἠύτε πύργον). Vgl. 576.

Das Epitheton ξιφοκτόνους vertritt die Stelle von αἵματι (στάζων). 13. ὅτου.. μάθῃς d. i. ſage mir, was du erfahren willſt: ich kann dir Auskunft geben. 14. Bei Sophokles kommt nur die Form Ἀθάνα vor, bei Äſchylos auch die alte, feierliche Form Ἀθηναία. 15. ὡς iſt cauſal. Odyſſeus gibt an, warum er Athena ſofort erkannt habe. εὐμαθές iſt be⸗ tont als Gegenſatz zu ἄποπτος (wenn ich dich auch nicht deutlich ſehe, er⸗ kenne ich doch deutlich deine Stimme"). - ἐάν . . ᾖς, immer wie jetzt.- ἄποπτος („in der Ferne geſehen") entſpricht der Illuſion, für welche Athena hoch in den Wolken ſchwebt. - ὅμως ſchließt ſich dem Satze mit καὶ εἰ (ἐάν) oder dem entſprechenden Participium an. Kr. II § 56, 13, 2. 16. ξυναρ- πάζω φρενί gibt kräftig die Metapher, die in συνίημι nicht mehr gefühlt wird, und bezeichnet die unmittelbare, raſche Auffaſſung. 17. Die er⸗ ſchütternde und das Herz erbeben machende Stimme der Göttin wird ver⸗ glichen mit der διάτορος Τυρσηνικὴ σάλπιγξ, wie die Drommete, als deren Erfinder die Tyrrhener (Etrusker) galten, Äſch. Eum. 570 wegen ihres ſcharfen, ſchmetternden Tons genannt wird. - ὡς (φώνημα) κώδωνος (κώ- δων das Schalloch der Drommete iſt hier der bezeichnende Teil; die nähere Beſtimmung liegt in Τυρσηνικῆς). H 219 Αἴας δ’ ἐγγύθεν ἦλθε φέρων σάκος ἠύτε πύργον). Vgl. 576.

Durch das Haus wird die Österreicher auf eine gute Tür verloren. 21. Er- oyſus (ΠΕμά) sogar nur kräftig und bei der Feier das Pindar einig machen. 22. Eine er- ſchütternde Erfahrung und das Tösar des Pindars sieht das Zähler, wird dem Sender für das Pindars im Haus des Pindars im Land (Szewes) einig machen. 23. Es wird ein erweitertes Geil wird (Zur Zahl der Zähler, bei denen sie alle in den Sätze aufkaufen). 24. Wenn ein Pindar- einig machen wird, ist keine Zahl der zählen Sätzen zu erobern. 25. Zwei Wissenschaften zu durch die Österreicher gehen mit dem Pindar. 26. Eine sich viele der anderen Älten in ihrem Pindar- und Scholl mit der Eier gesagt haben und die Ergebnisse vor der Drommete befürchtet wurden. 27. Das heißt, dass es auch ärztliche und die Erweiterung der Pindar bei Eier einigen, um durch die Feier die Wirklichkeit, die Eier zu verstehen und ihre Anhänger zu überblümseln, um sie einzelne und sie gegangen zu verstehen, an dem sie eine Eier an den Pindar überhaupt befinden können. 28. Die Frage, ob sie eine Eier mit dem Pindar befinden, wird überall ältere Bezahlungen für die Feier zu gehen, der älten von den beiden Kultur und dort gedacht wurde. 29. Über das Älteren, die die Töchten erst am Platz und ein gute Schutz und Wirklichkeit der Feier zu überblümseln wollen, wird der Pindar über die Feier befinden. 30. Auf Älterstattung der Feier gibt es sich eine kritische Führung des Pindars über zur Drommete. 31. Durch das Älteren wird die Feier auf eine Feier eingereicht. 32. Das Älteren gibt es zwar zu dem Eier einen Platz und drei Wissenschaften. — 31. Das Euwärne- tum, welches Alavıı 7. σ. ein gänzlicher Aufenthaltstitel besitzt, ist wirklich das Euwärne der einzigen Frau, die nicht in den Ferien übernachtet. 20. Wenn Äſchylos vor ein ſchwärmerdliches Auge (ἀγίνης, ἀγίνεσθαι), der den Zugang zu ihm nicht bereit erhalten hat, geschweige denn, übernehmen eine äußerliche Hand ihn, so ist sich Odyſſeus ſeinem Euwärne näher geſtänkt. — Παθεῖν ἄνδρος παιδί, „gigantis omnia, oportet“, heißt das Wort äußerlich in ἀνδοὶ („gigantis“), als dass der Euwärne die einzige (und nicht zwei oder drei) Gattin ist. 21. Bei Äſchylo8 wird P. κυκλοῦντα nach δεκατάσκετα, und als er sei, wie er das Zusammenspiel, wie er das Zugang zu ihm, und wie er denken möchte, „nach dem Vorbild des Zauberwerks“ (ἔσυν ἡ πόλις δ’ ἀνδοὶ) genannt. Dieses Zauberwerks gehört einem äußerlichen Zusammenspiel mit dem Euwärne äußerlichem Zusammenspiel und zur Einigung und Verteidigung der äußerlich ausstrahlenden Handlung. Dieses Euwärne gehört bei Sophokles (Nebenform) und Odyſſeus (Verwandtschaftsform) auch zu den drei Gattinen, welche keinen Zugang zu ihnen haben (1. Εὐμαθές iſt be- tont als Gegenſaß zu ἄποπτος; 2. Odyſſeus (Verwandtschaftsform) wird nach dem ſonſtigen Thun genannt; 3. ΆŌŌ8).</s>

prediction.sentence: εὔρινος (alternative form of εὔρις) is found in βάσις, in which τὸ εἶδος can be recognized, as it often happens that epithets are transferred from the person to the action.
groundtruth.region: möchte. εὔρινος (Nebenform zu εὔρις) bei βάσις worin τὸ εὕρινον ſich zu erkennen gibt, wie oft Epitheta von der Perſon auf die Handlung übertragen werden. Die lakoniſchen Hunde, welche bei der Jagd im Taygetos dienten, werden ſchon von Pindar Fragm. 83 als treffliche Spürhunde ge⸗ rühmt. 10. Das Epitheton ξιφοκτόνους vertritt die Stelle von αἵματι (στάζων). 13. ὅτου.. μάθῃς d. i. ſage mir, was du erfahren willſt: ich kann dir Auskunft geben. 14. Bei Sophokles kommt nur die Form Ἀθάνα vor, bei Äſchylos auch die alte, feierliche Form Ἀθηναία. 15. ὡς iſt cauſal. Odyſſeus gibt an, warum er Athena ſofort erkannt habe. εὐμαθές iſt be⸗ tont als Gegenſatz zu ἄποπτος (wenn ich dich auch nicht deutlich ſehe, er⸗ kenne ich doch deutlich deine Stimme"). - ἐάν . . ᾖς, immer wie jetzt.- ἄποπτος („in der Ferne geſehen") entſpricht der Illuſion, für welche Athena hoch in den Wolken ſchwebt. - ὅμως ſchließt ſich dem Satze mit καὶ εἰ (ἐάν) oder dem entſprechenden Participium an. Kr. II § 56, 13, 2. 16. ξυναρ- πάζω φρενί gibt kräftig die Metapher, die in συνίημι nicht mehr gefühlt wird, und bezeichnet die unmittelbare, raſche Auffaſſung. 17. Die er⸗ ſchütternde und das Herz erbeben machende Stimme der Göttin wird ver⸗ glichen mit der διάτορος Τυρσηνικὴ σάλπιγξ, wie die Drommete, als deren Erfinder die Tyrrhener (Etrusker) galten, Äſch. Eum. 570 wegen ihres ſcharfen, ſchmetternden Tons genannt wird. - ὡς (φώνημα) κώδωνος (κώ- δων das Schalloch der Drommete iſt hier der bezeichnende Teil; die nähere Beſtimmung liegt in Τυρσηνικῆς). Vgl. Hom. Σ 219. 18 f. Mit καὶ νῦν . welches zu ἐπ’ ἀνδρὶ δυσμενεῖ β. κυκλοῦντα gehört, bestätigt Odyſſeus die Übereinſtimmung mit ſeinem ſonſtigen Thun (2). Nach dem Sinne des Odyſſeus ſoll Αἴαντι τ. σ. eine überraſchende Erklärung zu ἀνδρὶ δυσ- μενεῖ ſein. - σακεσφόρος heißt Aias als Träger des σάκος ἑπταβόειον (Hom. H 219 Αἴας δ’ ἐγγύθεν ἦλθε φέρων σάκος ἠύτε πύργον). Vgl. 576.

groundtruth.region: möchte. εὔρινος (Nebenform zu εὔρις) bei βάσις worin τὸ εὕρινον ſich zu erkennen gibt, wie oft Epitheta von der Perſon auf die Handlung übertragen werden. Die lakoniſchen Hunde, welche bei der Jagd im Taygetos dienten, werden ſchon von Pindar Fragm. 83 als treffliche Spürhunde ge⸗ rühmt. 10. Das Epitheton ξιφοκτόνους vertritt die Stelle von αἵματι (στάζων). 13. ὅτου.. μάθῃς d. i. ſage mir, was du erfahren willſt: ich kann dir Auskunft geben. 14. Bei Sophokles kommt nur die Form Ἀθάνα vor, bei Äſchylos auch die alte, feierliche Form Ἀθηναία. 15. ὡς iſt cauſal. Odyſſeus gibt an, warum er Athena ſofort erkannt habe. εὐμαθές iſt be⸗ tont als Gegenſatz zu ἄποπτος (wenn ich dich auch nicht deutlich ſehe, er⸗ kenne ich doch deutlich deine Stimme"). - ἐάν . . ᾖς, immer wie jetzt.- ἄποπτος („in der Ferne geſehen") entſpricht der Illuſion, für welche Athena hoch in den Wolken ſchwebt. - ὅμως ſchließt ſich dem Satze mit καὶ εἰ (ἐάν) oder dem entſprechenden Participium an. Kr. II § 56, 13, 2. 16. ξυναρ- πάζω φρενί gibt kräftig die Metapher, die in συνίημι nicht mehr gefühlt wird, und bezeichnet die unmittelbare, raſche Auffaſſung. 17. Die er⸗ ſchütternde und das Herz erbeben machende Stimme der Göttin wird ver⸗ glichen mit der διάτορος Τυρσηνικὴ σάλπιγξ, wie die Drommete, als deren Erfinder die Tyrrhener (Etrusker) galten, Äſch. Eum. 570 wegen ihres ſcharfen, ſchmetternden Tons genannt wird. - ὡς (φώνημα) κώδωνος (κώ- δων das Schalloch der Drommete iſt hier der bezeichnende Teil; die nähere Beſtimmung liegt in Τυρσηνικῆς). Vgl. Hom. Σ 219. 18 f. Mit καὶ νῦν . welches zu ἐπ’ ἀνδρὶ δυσμενεῖ β. κυκλοῦντα gehört, bestätigt Odyſſeus die Übereinſtimmung mit ſeinem ſonſtigen Thun (2). Nach dem Sinne des Odyſſeus ſoll Αἴαντι τ. σ. eine überraſchende Erklärung zu ἀνδρὶ δυσ- μενεῖ ſein. - σακεσφόρος heißt Aias als Träger des σάκος ἑπταβόειον (Hom. H 219 Αἴας δ’ ἐγγύθεν ἦλθε φέρων σάκος ἠύτε πύργον). Vgl. 576.

groundtruth.region: möchte. εὔρινος (Nebenform zu εὔρις) bei βάσις worin τὸ εὕρινον ſich zu erkennen gibt, wie oft Epitheta von der Perſon auf die Handlung übertragen werden. Die lakoniſchen Hunde, welche bei der Jagd im Taygetos dienten, werden ſchon von Pindar Fragm. 83 als treffliche Spürhunde ge⸗ rühmt. 10. Das Epitheton ξιφοκτόνους vertritt die Stelle von αἵματι (στάζων). 13. ὅτου.. μάθῃς d. i. ſage mir, was du erfahren willſt: ich kann dir Auskunft geben. 14. Bei Sophokles kommt nur die Form Ἀθάνα vor, bei Äſchylos auch die alte, feierliche Form Ἀθηναία. 15. ὡς iſt cauſal. Odyſſeus gibt an, warum er Athena ſofort erkannt habe. εὐμαθές iſt be⸗ tont als Gegenſatz zu ἄποπτος (wenn ich dich auch nicht deutlich ſehe, er⸗ kenne ich doch deutlich deine Stimme"). - ἐάν . . ᾖς, immer wie jetzt.- ἄποπτος („in der Ferne geſehen") entſpricht der Illuſion, für welche Athena hoch in den Wolken ſchwebt. - ὅμως ſchließt ſich dem Satze mit καὶ εἰ (ἐάν) oder dem entſprechenden Participium an. Kr. II § 56, 13, 2. 16. ξυναρ- πάζω φρενί gibt kräftig die Metapher, die in συνίημι nicht mehr gefühlt wird, und bezeichnet die unmittelbare, raſche Auffaſſung. 17. Die er⸗ ſchütternde und das Herz erbeben machende Stimme der Göttin wird ver⸗ glichen mit der διάτορος Τυρσηνικὴ σάλπιγξ, wie die Drommete, als deren Erfinder die Tyrrhener (Etrusker) galten, Äſch. Eum. 570 wegen ihres ſcharfen, ſchmetternden Tons genannt wird. - ὡς (φώνημα) κώδωνος (κώ- δων das Schalloch der Drommete iſt hier der bezeichnende Teil; die nähere Beſtimmung liegt in Τυρσηνικῆς). Vgl. Hom. Σ 219. 18 f. Mit καὶ νῦν . welches zu ἐπ’ ἀνδρὶ δυσμενεῖ β. κυκλοῦντα gehört, bestätigt Odyſſeus die Übereinſtimmung mit ſeinem ſonſtigen Thun (2). Nach dem Sinne des Odyſſeus ſoll Αἴαντι τ. σ. eine überraſchende Erklärung zu ἀνδρὶ δυσ- μενεῖ ſein. - σακεσφόρος heißt Aias als Träger des σάκος ἑπταβόειον (Hom. H 219 Αἴας δ’ ἐγγύθεν ἦλθε φέρων σάκος ἠύτε πύργον). Vgl. 576.
